<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-934-660  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 934 660.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Dec 4 1989 v6 n48 p2(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Price hike permitted after carrier opens competition. (New YorkTelephone Co.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crockett, Barton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Attendees at the 1989 Communications Manager Assn conference werefighting for greater competition in the local loop, upset by ratechanges proposed by New York Telephone Co (NYT).andP;  A new tariff hasgiven NYT the right to increase the amount a user pays forprivate-line services by as much as 25 percent, as long as otherusers' rates decline and the total private-line revenue remainsconstant.andP;  NYT was given this flexible way of pricing incompensation for opening up competition in the local loop.andO;However, users oppose the change, despite the fact that morecompetition will be allowed.andP;  Carriers are concerned that pricesare dropping where the greatest potential for competition exists,and increasing where there is little competition.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   New York Telephone Co. (rates).andO;Topic:     Communication Managers AssociationPriceTelecommunicationsTelephone CompaniesLocal Communication.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>